To be more precise than your (as usual) rewritten header would suggest, the
new law permits civil marriages for anyone who doesn't qualify for a
religious marriage, i.e. which would include people who consider themselves
Jewish but are not Jewish in accordance with [Orthodox] halacha. So, someone
whom the Reform consider Jewish as a result of patrilineal descent, for
example, would qualify for a civil marriage. Interfaith marriages or
marriages where one or both of the partners is an R or C convert would
qualify for a civil marriage. Of course, if you, Jay, want to consider R and
C converts &quot;non-Jews&quot; (since your subject line suggests that civil marriage
will be permitted to non-Jews only) that is your prerogative, but I would
find that a little surprising coming from you.
Best regards,
---Cindy S.
