Steve, the decision as to who is Jewish rests not with the individual, but
with the rabbinate. I can't declare myself to be a non-Jew according to the
proposed law. The rabbanut will be the only body empowered to do that.

This proposed law needs to go through several committee readings and then
the knesset plenum (3 readings)  to become law. It is not guaranteed that
the O parties will agree (they listen to their political leaders more than
they listen to the chief rabbis). There is, in my view, a major pitfall
which the politicos will likely recognize at once.

At this time, the Israeli Supreme Court is (still) liberal. This may change
slightly, now that Aharon Barak has left, but perhaps not soon enough for
the Os.

The day after this law is passed, a lawsuit will very likely be filed with
the court, complaining against gross discrimination. If Dimitri is not
considered Jewish and may marry Natasha in an Israeli civil ceremony, why
can't I, Yossi, born in Israel to a Jewish mother,  who AM halachically
Jewish, not marry the same beautiful Natasha?

Why is the state forcing me to go to Cyprus to be married by a non-Jewish
non-Israeli civil servant when the state has the capability -- and the
institution -- for marrying me right here and now?

The court may not agree that this is discrimination. But it will be an
interesting fight.

Jay
