-------
The difference in the Jerusalem situation is that you have a busload of
people, men and women, who equally find the gender segregation desirable.
Special arrangements are made with the bus company that certain runs/certain
buses are separated by gender. By necessity, when there is segregation by
gender, one gender needs to sit in the front and the other in the back, or
one side of the aisle needs to be designated for men and the other for
women. There are gender segregated private buses in the USA as well (used by
the Orthodox communities in New York City), and it is my understanding that
they are indeed set up the latter way. The argument for women in the back of
the bus (versus the front) is that they sometimes like to nurse their babies
and would be unable to do so if they were up front where the men could see
them.

The issue in this situation was not the legitimacy of gender segregation in
and of itself but rather that the particular bus in question was not one of
the specially designated buses.

This is quite different from the situation in Montgomery where blacks were
forced to sit in the back of public buses against their will because of
discrimination. In Jerusalem, the religious women voluntarily want to be
gender segregated, insist on it, and this one woman was acting in opposition
to the will of the majority (including all the other women on the bus). In
the religious Jewish world, the movement is going toward increased gender
segregation, not less, and this is desired by both men and women.

This is not a situation where women are being forced to sit in the back of
the bus against their will and Miriam Shear's action is going to make a
statement for &quot;women's rights&quot; and change all of that and women are going to
thank her for it. The women on the bus were every bit as incensed as the
men. Totally different situation.
